          "body": "The figure of the *nasi* (prince) in Ezekiel's temple vision is one of the most studied features of chapters 40-48. Conspicuously, Ezekiel never calls him *melek* (king). The choice of *nasi* is a deliberate theological demotion: the future leader of Israel is a steward of the holy space, not its sovereign. He receives bounded land so that he cannot expropriate (45:8); he receives the people's contributions so that he can fund the worship calendar (45:16-17); and he provides a sin offering for *himself* at Passover (45:22) — he is not a sinless mediator but a sinner who participates in the atonement he provides. The vision of the prince in chapter 45 is a corrective portrait: Israel's leadership failures under the monarchy are architecturally prevented by the new order's design."
