          "title": "Commerce and holiness are not separate domains",
          "body": "The intrusion of commercial law into the middle of a temple vision (45:9-12) is not a digression. It is the chapter's sharpest pastoral argument. The same God who specifies the dimensions of the sanctuary specifies the weight of the shekel, the volume of the ephah, and the capacity of the bath. The prophetic background is dense: Amos 8:5 condemned those who made the ephah small and the shekel great; Micah 6:11 asked whether God can acquit dishonest scales; Ezekiel 22:12 named bribery and extortion as the sins that made exile necessary. The restored order does not allow the marketplace to operate by different rules than the altar. Just balances (*mozen tsedeq*) and just measures are the commercial extension of the holiness demanded at the sanctuary threshold. As Swindoll observed of the Mosaic law's similar structure: God does not draw a line between sacred duties and civil conduct because the whole life of His covenant people is to reflect His character."
