          "body": "The word *kipher* (make atonement) appears three times in the chapter — at 45:15, 17, and 20 — and it stitches together three otherwise disparate sections: the sacrificial-contribution schedule, the prince's festal provision, and the sanctuary purification rite. Atonement is not a single event in the restored calendar; it is the continuous provision by which a holy God and a sinful people are able to coexist in the same space. The blood applied to doorposts, altar corners, and gate-posts (45:19) maps atonement onto every threshold of the sacred precinct. The seventh-day repetition for inadvertent sin (45:20) shows that the provision covers not only deliberate transgression but the unintentional defilement that accumulates in ordinary human life. Peter Davids and Douglas Moo, writing on the New Testament's appropriation of this vocabulary, both note that *kipher* in the Levitical tradition is the semantic background for *hilasmos* (propitiation/expiation) in 1 John 2:2 and Romans 3:25 — the same logic of covering and clearing sin that makes fellowship with a holy God possible."
