          "body": "The critical interpretive question for Ezekiel 40-48, and for chapter 45 in particular, is how to read these chapters eschatologically. A traditional dispensational reading (Walvoord, Feinberg) takes the measurements and calendar prescriptions as literal details of a millennial temple yet to be built in the land of Israel. An amillennial/idealist reading (Vos, Hoekema, Beale) treats the vision as symbolic architecture whose fulfillment is the church as the temple of the Holy Spirit (1 Corinthians 3:16; Ephesians 2:21) and whose 'prince' is Christ. A modified symbolic reading notes the frank impossibility of certain measurements (ch. 47's river flowing from Jerusalem to the Dead Sea) and reads the entire vision as prophetic ideal — what Israel's worship *would have* looked like under covenant faithfulness, now fulfilled in the new covenant community. Orthodox commentators disagree here; the student is not served by a forced resolution. What is not in dispute is the theological substance: the chapter insists that God's holiness reorganizes every domain of life — space, governance, commerce, and time — and that access to Him requires both just conduct and continuous atonement. These realities are fulfilled in Christ whether one reads the vision as literal-millennial blueprint or as eschatological typology."
