    "intro": "Interpretation asks what the text *means* — moving from observation (what does it say?) to the author's intent in its original and canonical context. Ezekiel 45 sits at the climax of a vision (chs. 40-48) that is one of the most contested passages in prophetic literature. The movements below trace the chapter's four argument-sections in sequence, drawing on the historical context of the exile, the canonical weight of the Mosaic sacrificial system, and the points at which the chapter's logic connects forward to the New Testament's theology of holiness and atonement.",
