        "body": "The chapter opens with a land-allocation command issued in the context of the lot-division that chapter 47 will describe in full. Before any tribe receives its inheritance, a *terumah* — a lifted-out, consecrated portion — is set aside for the Lord. The word *terumah* carries Levitical force: in Leviticus 7 and Numbers 18, the *terumah* is the portion of the offering lifted toward God before the remainder is distributed. The same logic governs land: God's portion is not the residual after human needs are satisfied; it is the first-fruits allocation from which all other assignments derive their legitimacy.\n\nThe spatial arrangement that follows (vv. 2-7) is a set of nested zones. The outermost holy district (25,000 × 20,000 cubits) contains the priestly strip (25,000 × 10,000 cubits, v.4), beside which lies the Levitical strip of identical dimensions (v.5). South of these runs the city allotment (5,000 × 25,000 cubits, v.6), belonging to the whole house of Israel. The prince's land flanks the entire complex on east and west (v.7). Daniel Block (*The Book of Ezekiel, Chapters 25-48*, NICOT, 1998) observes that the spatial hierarchy mirrors the concentric holiness of the tabernacle's court-structure, now expanded to a regional scale: the nearer to the sanctuary, the more restricted and sacred the zone.\n\nThe theological payoff of the land arrangement comes in verse 8: 'so My princes shall no longer oppress My people.' The conjunction is crucial — the prince's defined *achuzzah* is not a reward for leadership but a structural prevention of tyranny. Pre-exilic Israel's history was scarred by royal land-seizure: Ahab and Naboth's vineyard (1 Kings 21) was the paradigm case; Ezekiel 22:25-29 catalogued the princes who had devoured people, taken treasures, and seized widows' property. The new order's land-map is designed so that the prince cannot repeat this because he already has enough — and it is bounded. Property rights in the restored community are not merely civic policy; they are the spatial expression of the command not to oppress.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Terumah* (lifted-out portion, 45:1, 6, 13) is the technical Levitical term for a dedicated contribution lifted toward God. *Nasi* (prince, 45:7, 8, 9) is deliberately chosen over *melek* (king) throughout chs. 40-48 — the demoted title encodes a theological claim about the future leader's subordinate role relative to the sanctuary. *Achuzzah* (possession, 45:5, 6, 7, 8) is the covenant-grant word used in Genesis 17:8 for Israel's land inheritance — its repetition here ties the restored allocation to the Abrahamic promise."
