        "excerpt": "Enough, you princes of Israel; put away violence and destruction, and practice justice and righteousness.",
        "body": "Verse 9 breaks the architectural register of the chapter with sudden prophetic confrontation. The word *rav* — 'Enough' — is the vocabulary of divine exasperation. The same exclamation occurs in Numbers 16:3 (Korah's rebellion), Deuteronomy 3:26 (Moses told he will not enter Canaan), and Isaiah 1:11 (God's rejection of meaningless sacrifice). It signals that a limit has been reached, that the pattern being addressed has continued long enough and will now end.\n\nThe indictment names four sins: *chamas* (violent brutality), *shod* (destruction, devastation), expropriating the people, and unjust commercial measures. The first two are the vocabulary of predatory power; the second two are its practical instruments. The princes of pre-exilic Israel had weaponized both: they seized land by force (*chamas*) and falsified the weights by which they extracted tribute (*ephah* and *bath* calibrated in their own favor). Amos 8:5 had exposed this precise combination — false weights in the marketplace serving the same lords who oppressed the poor at the gate. Micah 3:1-3 and 6:11 said the same. Ezekiel 22:29 had listed 'the people of the land' who 'practiced extortion and committed robbery.' Chapter 45's rebuke is not new — it is the accumulated prophetic verdict now embedded in the restored order's foundational charter.\n\nThe positive commands (v.9b) are *mishpat* and *tsedaqah* — justice and righteousness — the twin pillars of prophetic ethics from Amos 5:24 through Isaiah 9:7. These are not abstract virtues; they are demonstrated in calibrated scales (v.10), standardized volumetric measures (vv.11-12), and a fixed shekel weight (v.12). The detail of the commercial law is significant: the shekel of twenty gerahs, the maneh of sixty shekels (twenty + twenty-five + fifteen, v.12), and the equality of ephah and bath at one-tenth of a homer (v.11) are covenant-grade standards that the sanctuary's presence demands of the surrounding market. God's holiness does not stop at the sanctuary wall; it calibrates the scales in the city.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chamas* (violence, 45:9) is the term Genesis 6:11 uses for the moral state that provoked the flood — its appearance here is a strong signal that unjust governance is not a minor infraction but a covenant-threatening disorder. *Mishpat* and *tsedaqah* (justice and righteousness) form the standard prophetic word-pair for social order under covenant. *Tsedeq* (just, 45:10 ×3) is the same root as *tsedaqah* — the triple repetition in a single verse emphasizes that the commercial standard is not merely legal compliance but an expression of God's own righteousness."
