        "body": "Having rebuked the princes for taking what belongs to the people (vv.9-12), the text now describes the fiscal arrangement by which the restored worship economy will function (vv.13-17). The people contribute a defined portion of their agricultural produce — one-sixth of an ephah per homer of wheat and barley (v.13), one-tenth of a bath of oil per kor (v.14), one sheep per two hundred from the flock (v.15). These contributions go *to the prince* (v.16), who in turn provides the entire sacrificial apparatus for the worship calendar (v.17). The prince is not an extractor but a conduit: the people's tithe-like contribution funds the prince's liturgical obligation.\n\nThe significance of verse 17's list — burnt offerings, grain offerings, drink offerings, sin offerings, peace offerings — is that the prince must provide all five major offering types for every feast, every new moon, and every sabbath. The breadth of the obligation is matched by the comprehensiveness of the stated purpose: 'to make atonement for the house of Israel.' Atonement is the telos of the entire sacrificial economy. The prince's role in facilitating it makes him not a ritual performer (the priests do the actual sacrificial work, as chapters 43-44 specified) but a liturgical patron — ensuring that the material provision for Israel's access to God is never lacking.\n\nThis section directly inverts the pre-exilic dynamic. Israel's pre-exilic kings had used the temple for political legitimation (Solomon's inaugural acts, Ahaz's altar modifications in 2 Kings 16:10-16, Manasseh's desecrations in 2 Kings 21) and had extracted from the temple's treasury when convenient. The new prince's relationship to the sanctuary is strictly one of provision, not exploitation. He gives to it; it does not serve him. Calvin (*Commentaries on the Prophet Ezekiel*, 1565) observed that this section is a sustained exposition of the servant-leadership principle that pervades Ezekiel's entire prophecy against the shepherds of Israel (Ezekiel 34).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Kipher* (make atonement, 45:15, 17) is the Piel of *kaphar* — to cover, to purge, to wipe clean. It is the technical term of the Levitical sacrificial system (Leviticus 1:4; 4:20, 26, 31; 16:6, 11, 24) and is the Hebrew background of the Greek *hilaskomai* / *hilasmos* (1 John 2:2; Romans 3:25). *Moed* (appointed feast, 45:17) means a divinely scheduled meeting-time — the feasts are not human inventions but divine appointments for encounter with God."
