        "body": "The chapter's second major oracle formula ('Thus says the Lord God,' v.18) opens the festal calendar with an act that has no precise parallel in the Mosaic law: a sanctuary purification on the first day of the first month (Nisan 1), followed by a repetition on the seventh day for inadvertent sin (v.20). The nearest Mosaic analog is the annual Day of Atonement (Leviticus 16), which purified the tabernacle on the tenth of the seventh month. Ezekiel's calendar places an additional sanctuary-cleansing at the very beginning of the year, making the first week of the sacred calendar a period of comprehensive atonement before the regular worship cycle resumes.\n\nThe rite is precise: a bull without blemish (*tamim* — the standard perfection-requirement, Leviticus 1:3, 10; 3:1, 6), whose blood the priest applies to the doorposts of the house, the four corners of the altar's ledge, and the posts of the inner court gate (v.19). The blood application to thresholds is reminiscent of the Passover blood on the doorposts (Exodus 12:22-23) but functions here as a purification of the sacred boundaries rather than a protection from judgment. Every point of entry into the sacred precinct — house, altar, inner gate — is marked with atoning blood at the year's beginning.\n\nVerse 20 adds the pastoral note that the rite is repeated on the seventh day 'for everyone who goes astray or is naive.' *Shagah* (to stray, err) and *peti* (naive, simple, unaware) are the vocabulary of unintentional sin — the same category covered by the Mosaic sin-offering for inadvertent transgressions (Leviticus 4:2, 13, 22, 27; Numbers 15:27-29). The repeated purification shows that the restored order is not naively optimistic about human sinlessness even in the presence of God's glory; it provides structurally for the defilement that attaches to ordinary human life. The year begins with atonement and is regularly refreshed by it.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Tamim* (without blemish, 45:18, 23) — whole, complete, without defect. The same word used of Noah ('blameless,' Genesis 6:9), of Abraham's covenant-keeping ('blameless,' Genesis 17:1), and of the Passover lamb (Exodus 12:5). *Chata* (purify, cleanse, 45:18) is the denominative verb from *chattaah* (sin offering) — 'to de-sin,' to perform the sin-offering purification rite. *Shagah* (go astray, 45:20) and *peti* (naive) together cover the inadvertent sin category of Leviticus 4-5."
