        "title": "Passover and Tabernacles — redemptive history framing the restored year",
        "range": "45:21-25",
        "excerpt": "In the first month, on the fourteenth day of the month, you shall have the Passover, a feast of seven days; unleavened bread shall be eaten.",
        "body": "The chapter closes with the two great pilgrimage feasts that bracket the sacred year: Passover (first month, fourteenth day, vv.21-24) and Tabernacles/Booths (seventh month, fifteenth day, v.25). Both are prescribed as seven-day events; both require the same sacrificial provision from the prince — seven bulls and seven rams without blemish daily as burnt offerings, a male goat daily as a sin offering, and grain offerings (an ephah per bull and per ram) with oil (a hin per ephah). The identical prescriptions for both feasts signal that the restored worship calendar has a deliberate symmetry: what the first month commemorates (redemption from Egypt) and what the seventh month celebrates (God's provision in the wilderness, the harvest completed) are held together as the two poles of Israel's redemptive narrative.\n\nThe prince's role at Passover is pastorally significant: on the fourteenth day 'the prince shall provide for himself and all the people of the land a bull for a sin offering' (v.22). He is not exempt from the need for atonement. He participates in the sin-offering that opens the feast. This is the antithesis of the priestly-royal figure who stands above the need for cleansing; it is the portrait of a leader who acknowledges his own sinfulness and publicly enters the same provision that sustains the whole community. The contrast with the high priest of Hebrews is instructive: Hebrews 7:27 notes that the Levitical high priests had to offer sacrifices 'first for his own sins and then for the sins of the people,' whereas Christ 'has no need daily... to offer up sacrifices for His own sins.' Ezekiel's prince requires the sin offering; the ultimate Prince does not — the typology points forward.\n\nThe Feast of Tabernacles (v.25) receives abbreviated treatment — 'at the feast he shall provide like this,' mirroring the Passover prescriptions. The brevity is not dismissiveness; the identity of the offerings signals that the theological logic is the same for both feasts. What changes is the memorial content: Passover recalls the redemption-event; Tabernacles recalls the wilderness journey and the ingathering of harvest (Leviticus 23:39-43). Together they rehearse the full arc of Israel's story — brought out of bondage, sustained through the wilderness, brought into the land — now retold in the context of the restored sanctuary. As Tim Keller has noted in his treatment of the Old Testament feasts, the festivals are not religious obligations bolted onto ordinary life; they are the annual liturgical rehearsal of the community's identity as a people who were nowhere and are now somewhere, who were enslaved and are now free, who are sinful and are continuously cleansed.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Pesach* (Passover, 45:21) — the passing-over of the destroyer (Exodus 12:13); the foundational redemption event of Israel's national identity. *Matstsah* (unleavened bread, 45:21) — the bread of haste and affliction (Deuteronomy 16:3), eaten throughout the seven days as a memory-rite. *Sukkot* (Tabernacles/Booths) is not named in the NASB text of 45:25 but is identified by its date (seventh month, fifteenth day) and seven-day duration (Leviticus 23:34). The prince's daily *olah* (burnt offerings) of seven bulls and seven rams throughout both feasts expresses the completeness (seven) of total consecration offered to God during Israel's most sacred commemorations."
